Promise.resolve : we use it to directly return data if cache has the data ,no need to hit the actual api (so resolve converts normal data which is in cache into fullflled Promises or if its promise in cache then kept as it is )
Promise.reject
both of above are used to directly return promise and can be hanled in .then() and .catch()
and imp thing is you need to throw error from reject only that goes to catch , if you throw error from resolve it dont go to .catch() and not even tracked by try catch block  , it goes to .then()

Promise.resolve() has 2 purpose it will 
1. Create a resolved promise from a plain value:
Promise.resolve(42);        // Promise that resolves with 42
Promise.resolve('hello');   // Promise that resolves with 'hello'
Promise.resolve();          // Promise that resolves with undefined

2. Normalize any value into a proper Promise (safety wrapper):
const p = Promise.reject('error');
Promise.resolve(p);  // still rejected вҖ” just ensures it's a real Promise

const thenable = { then: (cb) => cb(10) };
Promise.resolve(thenable);  // converts thenable вҶ’ real Promise

